<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="135" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,150,861]" pageId="6" pageNumber="135">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,449,150,176]" pageId="6" pageNumber="135">Redescription. Male.</emphasis>
In addition to the characters mentioned in the generic description: 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1215,1344,150,176]" pageId="6" pageNumber="135">Coloration</emphasis>
. Brown with grayish spots; pleura and sternites of the thorax yellow. The outter border of the fore-, middle femora and the dorsal border of the tibiae are outlined in black; the hind femur has a midline from the base to the middle of their length outlined in black (
<figureCitation box="[437,528,258,284]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[211,1376,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-21@5.[211,1376,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Pepumiri brasiliensis (Beier, 1962) n. comb. Male holotype. A. Habitus in lateral and B. Dorsal views respectively. C. Terminalia in lateral and D. Ventral view. “© by Natural History Museum of Los Angeles County, U.S.A / G.A. Kung; published with permission.”" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6037017" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6037017/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="135">Fig. 2A</figureCitation>
). The tegminae have a black background and yellowish venation, except for the stridulating crest, which is reddish-brown (
<figureCitation box="[647,738,294,320]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[211,1376,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-21@5.[211,1376,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Pepumiri brasiliensis (Beier, 1962) n. comb. Male holotype. A. Habitus in lateral and B. Dorsal views respectively. C. Terminalia in lateral and D. Ventral view. “© by Natural History Museum of Los Angeles County, U.S.A / G.A. Kung; published with permission.”" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6037017" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6037017/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="135">Fig. 2B</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[762,826,294,320]" pageId="6" pageNumber="135">Head</emphasis>
with normal development, the maxillary palps’ first, second, and third segments have similar size; the fifth segment is the longest and dilates towards the apex. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1341,1430,330,356]" pageId="6" pageNumber="135">Thorax</emphasis>
. The anterior margin of the pronotum is round and extends moderately over the head; the posterior margin is slightly curved, and the pronotal disc is not elevated in the posterior zone (metazone) and with a shallow sulcus (
<figureCitation box="[1334,1423,402,428]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[211,1376,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-21@5.[211,1376,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Pepumiri brasiliensis (Beier, 1962) n. comb. Male holotype. A. Habitus in lateral and B. Dorsal views respectively. C. Terminalia in lateral and D. Ventral view. “© by Natural History Museum of Los Angeles County, U.S.A / G.A. Kung; published with permission.”" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6037017" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6037017/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="135">Fig. 2B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,150,861]" pageId="6" pageNumber="135">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,227,438,464]" pageId="6" pageNumber="135">Wings</emphasis>
. Rs vein indistinguishable; stridulating crest almost straight and thickened; the mirror of both tegmina have a similar size, and they are oblong and membranous (
<figureCitation box="[748,836,474,500]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[211,1376,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-21@5.[211,1376,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Pepumiri brasiliensis (Beier, 1962) n. comb. Male holotype. A. Habitus in lateral and B. Dorsal views respectively. C. Terminalia in lateral and D. Ventral view. “© by Natural History Museum of Los Angeles County, U.S.A / G.A. Kung; published with permission.”" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6037017" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6037017/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="135">Fig. 2B</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[856,912,474,500]" pageId="6" pageNumber="135">Legs</emphasis>
. Fore-femur armed with six spines only on the inner margin; the fore-tibia with eight spines on each ventral margin. Mid-femur with five ventral spines on the outer margin; and the mid-tibia with six ventral spines on each ventral margin. Hind femur with eight ventral spines on the outer margin; hind tibia with nine spines on both dorsal margins. All genicular lobes are armed, except the outer genicular lobe of the mid-femur; all spines of the femur and hind tibiae are black. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1124,1241,618,644]" pageId="6" pageNumber="135">Abdomen</emphasis>
. The tenth tergite extends moderately in the central part of the posterior border. Cerci thickened, slightly dorso-ventrally compressed, curved slightly inwards, and armed with two spines close to the apex of the inner margin (
<figureCitation box="[1149,1237,690,716]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[211,1376,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-21@5.[211,1376,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Pepumiri brasiliensis (Beier, 1962) n. comb. Male holotype. A. Habitus in lateral and B. Dorsal views respectively. C. Terminalia in lateral and D. Ventral view. “© by Natural History Museum of Los Angeles County, U.S.A / G.A. Kung; published with permission.”" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6037017" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6037017/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="135">Fig. 2C</figureCitation>
). Subgenital plate with a “V” shaped notch in the posterior edge, and the cylindrical styles have a similar thickness from the base to the apex (
<figureCitation box="[261,351,762,788]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[211,1376,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-21@5.[211,1376,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Pepumiri brasiliensis (Beier, 1962) n. comb. Male holotype. A. Habitus in lateral and B. Dorsal views respectively. C. Terminalia in lateral and D. Ventral view. “© by Natural History Museum of Los Angeles County, U.S.A / G.A. Kung; published with permission.”" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6037017" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6037017/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="135">Fig. 2D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
